"I came today to vote on the future of the country, for young people in Macedonia, so that they can live freely under the umbrella of the European Union, because it means safer lives for all of us," said Olivera Georgiyevska, 79, in Skopje.
The vote is not legally binding, but enough Members of Parliament have said that they will abide by the result of the vote and assert it.
The name change would require a two-thirds majority in parliament.
