John Edward: Language skills are essential for global citizens
Scotland’s independent schools have many great academic achievements behind them, and it has continued in 2018 with yet another series of outstanding exam results, further enhanced by individual and collective success in sports, arts, music and other endeavors in the local community.
With up to 30,000 students around Scotland, these schools, represented by The Scottish Council of Independent Schools (SCIS), strive to deliver the best level of service to their students and parents.
The independent schools try to prepare their students for further and higher education, their chosen careers and their place as global citizens.
As an education sector that can put together and implement a tailor-made curriculum, we find that modern languages remain a popular topic in schools.
Nelson Mandela said, "If you talk to a man in a language he understands, it hits his head.
If you talk to him in his own language, it hits his heart."
It’s an important reminder that we can’t just stick to English when we want to build relationships and trust among people from other countries.
We can see from the most recent exam results this year that languages rank highest in the statistics with the most passed exams in the independent schools.
A total of 68 percent of the students who studied foreign languages received the high grade of A.
The data collected by SCIS' 74 member schools showed that 72 percent of students received grade A in Mandarin, while 72 percent of those who studied German, 69 percent of those who studied French, and 63 percent of those who studied Spanish also received an A.
It shows that independent schools in Scotland support foreign languages as important competences that children and young people will undoubtedly need in the future.
Language is now perceived as the same level as STEM subjects (science, technology, engineering and mathematics) in independent schools’ pensa and elsewhere.
A 2014 survey by the UK Commission for Employment and Skills found that among the reasons employers could not fill vacancies, 17% had a lack of language skills.
Therefore, language skills are becoming increasingly important in preparing young people for their future careers.
More job opportunities will require language skills in the future, and these skills are essential in a globalised world.
Whatever career the young people choose, if they have learned another language, they have a great advantage in the future with a lifelong skill like this.
The ability to communicate directly with people from other countries automatically give a multilingual person a head start to the competition.
According to a YouGov poll of over 4,000 respondents in the UK in 2013, 75 per cent could not speak a foreign language well enough to hold a conversation, and French is the only language spoken by a multi-digit percentage, 15 per cent.
Therefore, it is important to invest in language teaching for those who are children today.
When you can speak more languages, especially languages from developing countries, it gives children a better chance of finding meaningful work.
In Scotland, schools differ in which languages are taught.
A number of schools focus on the more classical modern languages, while others teach languages that are expected to be most important to the UK when looking ahead to 2020, such as Mandarin or Japanese.
No matter what your child is interested in, there will always be a number of languages to choose from at independent schools with teachers who are specialists in the field.
Scottish independent schools are dedicated to providing a learning environment that prepares children and gives them the skills required to succeed, whatever the future holds.
At present, it cannot be denied that languages continue to be truly important for the country's future in a global business environment, and this must be reflected in the degree programmes.
Modern languages should really be considered "international communication skills".
Independent schools will continue to offer this choice, this diversity and this distinction to the youth of Scotland.
Il faut bien le faire.
John Edward is the head of the Scottish Council of Independent Schools
