North Korea says it will not disarm unilaterally if there is no confidence
North Korea's foreign minister told the UN on Saturday that continued sanctions reinforce their mistrust of the United States and that the country will not give up their nuclear weapons unilaterally in such conditions.
Ri Yong Ho told the worldwide organization's general assembly that North Korea had shown "substantial goodwill" within the past year, e.g., by stopping nuclear and missile tests, dismantling an area for nuclear tests and promising not to further develop nuclear weapons and nuclear technology.
"We have not seen a similar reaction from the United States," he said.
"Without confidence in the United States, there is no confidence in our national security and under such conditions, there is no chance that we ourselves will take the first step and disarm unilaterally."
While Ri reiterated well-known North Korean complaints about Washington's opposition to a "phased" approach to nuclear disarmament, in which North Korea would be rewarded if they took gradual steps. But his speech seemed important as it did not unequivocally reject unilateral disarmament, as has been the case in the past from Pyongyang.
Ri referred to a joint statement by Kim Jong Un and Donald Trump at the first ever summit between a sitting U.S. president and a North Korean leader in Singapore on June 12, where Kim promised to work "nuclear disarmament on the Korean peninsula" while Trump promised to guarantee North Korea's security.
North Korea has called for a formal end to the Korean War that took place in 1950-53, but the United States has said that Pyongyang must first give up their nuclear weapons.
Washington has also shown resistance in terms of softening up tough international sanctions against North Korea.
"The United States insists on 'nuclear disarmament first' and expands the pressure of sanctions to achieve their purpose by force, even opposing the 'declaration of the end of the war'," Ri said.
"The perception that sanctions can bring us to our knees is a pipe dream among people who don't know who we are.
But the problem is that the continued sanctions reinforce our mistrust."
Ri did not mention plans for another summit between Kim and Trump, as the US leader highlighted at the United Nations earlier this week.
The minister instead highlighted three meetings between Kim and South Korean leader Moon Jae-in within the past five months, adding, "If nuclear disarmament were to be negotiated with South Korea and not the United States, the negotiations would not be so stale."
Nevertheless, the tone of Ri's speech was very different from last year, where he told the UN General Assembly that firing North Korea's missiles at the U.S. mainland was inevitable after "Mr. Evil President" Trump called Kim a "rocket man" on a suicide mission.
Last year, Trump threatened at the United Nations with the "total destruction" of North Korea, but this year he praised Kim for showing courage in terms of disarmament, but said there is still much to be done and that the sanctions need to remain until North Korea disarms.
On Wednesday, Trump said he did not have a schedule for these actions, but said "It doesn't matter whether it takes two years, three years or five months."
China and Russia believe that the UN Security Council should reward Pyongyang for the steps taken.
U.S. Secretary of State Mike Pompeo told the U.N. Security Council on Thursday that "the Security Council must maintain sanctions with conviction and without error until we achieve total, final, confirmed nuclear disarmament."
Since 2006, the Security Council has unanimously increased economic sanctions against North Korea in an effort to stop Pyongyang's missile and nuclear weapons program.
