Launched in 2012, the Global Citizen Festival is an extension of the Global Poverty Project, an international advocacy organization that fights to end poverty by increasing the number of active opponents.
To receive a free ticket to the event (if you do not want to pay for a VIP ticket), concertgoers must perform a number of tasks or "actions". E.g. do volunteer work, write to a world leader, make a phone call or some other meaningful action that can raise awareness about the goal of ending poverty.
But how successful has Global Citizen been, now that they have 12 years left to reach the goal?
Does the idea of rewarding people with a free concert create real change, or is it just another case of so-called “clicktivism” – meaning that people feel they are making a difference by signing a petition online or doing a Twitter post?
Global Citizen reports that since 2011, they have recorded more than 19 million “actions” from their members targeting various targets.
They believe that these actions have spurred world leaders to make binding targets and policies equivalent to more than $37 billion, which by 2030 is expected to have affected more than 2.25 billion people.
In early 2018, the group listed 390 goals and actions that had been created due to their actions, amounting to over $10 billion that had already been paid or collected.
The group estimates that these funds have so far had a direct impact on nearly 649 million people worldwide.
One of the main goals is The Power of Nutrition, which is a collaboration between investors and actionable individuals. They strive to “help children live out their full potential” and promise $35 million to alleviate nutrition problems in Rwanda after receiving more than 4,700 tweets from Global Citizens.
“With the help of the British government, donors, governments of other countries, and world citizens like you, the social injustice of malnutrition can become a footnote in the history books,” Tracey Ullman, the ambassador for The Power of Nutrition, told the audience at a concert in London in April 2018.
The group also said that the UK government has now promised funds to improve nutrition for mothers and children after receiving more than 5,000 calls online. This project, Power of Nutrition, will help five million mothers and children with advice on nutrition.
In response to one of the website's frequently asked questions, which reads, "What makes you think we can end extreme poverty?",
wrote the Global Citizen: "It will be a long and hard fight, and sometimes we will stumble and make mistakes.
But as with the civil rights movement and the movements against apartheid, it will succeed because we are stronger together."
