What is unique about the personal online data collection is that it is entirely up to the user to decide who can access the specific information.
The company calls it “personal empowerment through data.”
The idea of Inrupt, according to the company’s CEO, John Bruce, is to pool resources, processes and capabilities to make Solid accessible to everyone.
The company currently consists of Berners-Lee, Bruce, a security platform purchased by IBM, some software developers on a project contract and a community of volunteer programmers.
Starting this week, technology developers around the world can create their own decentralized apps using the tools available on Inrupt’s website.
Berners-Lee says he and his team aren’t talking to “Facebook or Google about whether or not they should change everything completely so that all of their business models suddenly become redundant.”
"We're not asking for their permission."
Berners-Lee’s mission is to offer commercial energy and an ecosystem that can ensure the integrity and quality of the new internet being built on Solid.
In 1994, Berners-Lee changed the Internet when he started the World Wide Web Consortium at the Massachusetts Institute of Technology.
