Bernard Vann: Ecclesiastical recipient of the Victoria Cross from World War I celebrated
The Church of England's only vicar who won the Victoria Cross by fighting during World War I is celebrated in his hometown 100 years later.
Lieutenant-Colonel and Reverend Bernard Wann won the Order on September 29, 1918, during the attack at Bellenglise and Lehaucourt.
However, he was killed four days later by a sniper and was never told that he had won the highest English military order.
On Saturday, a memorial stone was unveiled by his two grandchildren at a parade in Rushden, Northamptonshire.
Michael Vann, one of his grandchildren, said it was "incredibly symbolic" that the stone was unveiled exactly 100 years after his grandfather's order-winning feat.
According to the London Gazette, on 29 September 1918 Lieutenant Colonel Vann led his battalion across the Canal de Saint-Quentin "through a very thick fog and under heavy fire from machine guns and artillery."
He later ran up to the front line and led his people forward with the "greatest manhood" before attacking one artilleryman alone and incapacitating three guns.
Lieutenant Colonel Vann was killed by a German sniper on 4 October 1918 – just a month before the end of the war.
Michael Vann, 72, said his grandfather's actions were "something I knew I could never live up to, but that makes me humble."
He and his brother James Vann also laid a wreath after the parade, which was led by the Brentwood Imperial Youth Band.
Michael Vann stated that he "felt very honored to attend the parade" and added that "the support of all these people emphasizes the true heroism."
MMA fans stayed up all night to see Bellator 206, but instead got Gurli Gris
Imagine staying up all night to see the star-studded Bellator 206 and being denied the main event.
There were 13 matches on the programme from San Jose, including six matches on the main programme, and they were shown overnight in England on Channel 5.
At 6 a.m., when Gegard Mousasi and Rory MacDonald were getting ready to meet, viewers in England were somewhat surprised when the transmission switched to show Gurli Gris.
Some were unimpressed after they had stayed awake until the early morning for this particular match.
A fan on Twitter described the switch to a children's cartoon as "a kind of sick joke."
"According to legislation, this content was not appropriate at 6 a.m., which is why they had to switch to children's programs," said Dave Schwartz, Bellator's senior vice president when asked about the broadcast.
"'Grisen Gurli', yes".
Bellator’s CEO, Scott Coker, said they will work to include English viewers in the planning going forward.
"When thinking about the rerun, I think we can make it work," Coker said.
"But it's six o'clock Sunday morning over there, and we won't find a solution to that until Sunday our time, Monday their time.
But we're working on it.
Believe me, when the change was made, I got a lot of messages, and they were not all friendly.
We tried to fix it, we thought it was a technical glitch.
In fact, it was the law.
I can promise you it won’t happen next time.
We just have five games instead of six, like we usually do, we tried to give our fans something extra, and then we went over time.
It's an unfortunate situation."
Desert Island Discs: Tom Daley had "minority" over sexuality
Olympic diver Tom Daley says he felt inferior to everyone else in his upbringing because of his sexuality, but that motivated him to succeed.
The 24-year-old said that he didn't realize until he got into the larger classes that "everyone's not like me."
When he was on Radio 4's first Desert Island Discs with Lauren Laverne, he said he was talking about gay rights to give others "hope".
He also said that he was less interested in winning the Olympics after becoming a parent.
The regular host of the long-running radio show, Kirsty Young, has taken some months off due to illness.
Daley was a guest on Laverne's first program and said he felt "less valuable" than everyone else in his upbringing because "it was not socially accepted to like boys and girls."
He said, "Until today, the feelings of feeling worthy and feeling different have been the things that have given me the strength to be successful."
He wanted to prove that he was "something," he said, so he didn't disappoint everyone when they got to know his sexuality.
The dual Olympic bronze winner has become a high-profile LGBT campaigner and used his participation at this year's Commonwealth Games in Australia to appeal for a decriminalisation of homosexuality in several countries.
He said he spoke out because he felt lucky to be able to live openly without negative consequences, and he would give others "hope".
The triple world champion said he had been "surprised" when he fell in love with a man – the American filmmaker Dustin Lance Black, whom he met in 2013.
Last year, Daley married the Oscar winner, who is 20 years older than him, but said the age difference had never been a problem.
He said it’s hard to find someone the same age who has experienced similar ups and downs when you go through so much at such a young age – he went to his first Olympics at 14, and his father died of cancer three years later.
The couple became parents in June to a son named Robert Ray Black-Daley, and Daley said that "his whole perspective" had changed".
"If you had asked me last year, it would all be about me winning a gold medal," he said.
"But there are more important things than Olympic gold medals.
My Olympic gold medal is Robbie."
His son has the same name as his father, Robert, who died in 2011 at the age of 40 after being diagnosed with brain cancer.
Daley said his father did not accept his death, and one of the last things he asked was if they had been given tickets for London 2012 – as he would be sitting in the front row.
"I couldn't tell him he wouldn't be there by then.
I held his hand when his breathing stopped, and it first dawned on me that he wasn't immortal when he stopped breathing and was dead," he said.
The following year, Daley competed in the 2012 Olympics and won bronze.
“I just knew it was what I had dreamed of all my life – diving in front of a home crowd at the Olympics. There was nothing that could beat that feeling,” he said.
It was also the inspiration for his first song choice – Proud by Heather Small – which had meant a lot during the run-up to the Olympics and still gave him goosebumps.
Desert Island Discs runs on BBC Radio 4 on Sunday at 11:15 a.m. BST.
Unsharp Mickelson on the bench for the Ryder Cup on Saturday
American Phil Mickelson sets a record on Sunday when he plays his 47th match in the Ryder Cup, but he must do something about the form if it is not to be a sad milestone.
Mickelson, who sets a record for the 12th time in the competition, which is held every 2 years, was put on the bench by captain Jim Furyk due to Saturday's fourballs and foursomes.
Instead of being at the center of events for the United States as usual, the five-time grand winner had to act as a cheerleader and rehearse his game in the hopes of correcting the slips.
Even at the peak of his career, he did not have the most straight drive, which is why the 48-year-old is not a perfect match for the course at Le Golf National, where the long rough often penalizes stray shots.
And if the pitch wasn’t a big enough mouthful, Mickelson will face the ever-accurate winner of the British Open Francesco Molinari, who has teamed up with newcomer Tommy Fleetwood to win all four matches this week.
If the Americans who start the 12 singles games start strong, Mickelson's fight may be crucial.
Furyk expressed unsurprising confidence in his teammate.
"He understood his role completely today, gave me a pat on the back, put his arm around me and said he would be ready tomorrow," Furyk said.
“He has a lot of faith in himself.”
He is in the Hall of Fame and has given so much to these teams in the past – and also this week.
I didn't think he'd play two games.
I thought he was going to play more, but that’s how it went, and that’s how it should be.
He wants to be out there like everyone else.”
On Sunday, Mickelson beats Nick Faldo's record for most games played in the Ryder Cup.
It could be the end of a Ryder Cup career that has never quite matched his individual performance.
Mickelson has 18 wins, 20 defeats and seven draws, though Furyk said his presence contributes something indefinable.
"He's funny, he's sarcastic, witty, he likes sticking to people, and he's good to have in the team room," he explained.
"I also think the younger players had fun playing against him this week, which was fun to watch.
He contributes much more than just the game."
European captain Thomas Bjørn knows that great lead can quickly disappear
European captain Thomas Bjørn knows from experience that a solid lead before the last day of the Ryder Cup singles match can quickly become nerve-wracking.
The Dane made his debut in 1997 in Valderrama, where a team led by Seve Ballesteros had a lead of five points over the Americans, but was just about to be caught up before the finish line with a win of 141–2-131–2.
"You keep reminding yourself that we had a nice lead in Valderrama, we had a nice lead in Brookline, where we lost, and in Valderrama, where we only just won", says Bjørn after seeing the 2018 team win both 5-3 Friday and yesterday for a total lead of 10-6 at Le Golf National.
The story tells me and the rest of the team that it's not over.
It's going to be full tomorrow.
Go out and do everything right.
It's not over until you have the points on the board.
We have a goal and that is to try to win the trophy and that is where our focus lies.
I’ve always said that I’m focused on the 12 players on our side, but we’re also aware of what’s on the other side – the best golfers in the world.”
Rejoiced by his players' performance on a difficult pitch, Bjorn added, "I don't take any of this for granted.
Tomorrow is a new challenge.
Tomorrow, it’s the individual performances that count, and that’s something else entirely.
It’s great to be out there with a partner when things are going well, but when you’re out there alone, you’re tested on all parameters as a golfer.
That’s what the players need to understand – bring out the best in yourself tomorrow.
Now you must leave your partner, for he must also bring out the best in himself."
It looks different for opponent Jim Furyk, who hopes for better individual performance than in the partner game with the exception of Jordan Spieth and Justin Thomas, who won three out of four points.
Furyk himself has experienced reversals on the last day, first on the winning team in Brookline, before losing when Europe made the "Miracle on the Medinah".
"I remember every word," he said when asked how captain Ben Crenshaw had spoken to his players before the final day in 1999.
"We have 12 important games tomorrow, but you want to have a good start, as you saw at Brookline, as you saw at Medinah.
When momentum has found a direction, it puts a great deal of pressure on the middle fights.
We put our team together in relation to that and put the players on the pitch in the order we feel like. We try to create magic tomorrow."
Thomas has been tasked with trying to lead the rebound and faces Rory McIlroy in the top fight, while Paul Casey, Justin Rose, Jon Rahm, Tommy Fleetwood and Ian Poulter and the other Europeans play in the first half of the order.
"I chose this group of players in this order because I think it secures us all the way through," Bjørn said of his choice of singles players.
Germany's new warship launched
The German Navy’s newest frigate should have been ready in 2014 to replace warships from the Cold War. But the Germans must wait at least a year yet due to technical problems and an escalating price, local media writes.
The deployment of the largest ship in the brand new Baden-Wuerttemberg class of frigates, the "Rhineland-Pfalz", has been postponed to the first half of 2019 according to the newspaper Die Zeit, citing a military spokesman.
The ship should have joined the fleet in 2014, but after-delivery problems have plagued the ambitious project.
The four ships of the Baden-Wuerttemberg class, which the fleet ordered back in 2007, will replace the aging frigates of the Bremen class.
About them you know that they will have a powerful cannon, a large selection of anti-aircraft and anti-ship missiles, as well as stealth technologies such as reduced radar, infrared and acoustic signatures.
Another important feature of the newest frigates is a minor need for maintenance: it should be possible to have the frigates away from home ports for up to two years.
But the repeated delays mean that the advanced warships – which are said to make Germany appear to be an overseas power – will already be obsolete when deployed, writes Die Zeit.
The failed F125 frigate made headlines last year when the German Navy officially refused to take the ship into service and returned it to the Blohm & Voss shipyard in Hamburg.
It was the first time the Navy delivered a ship back to the shipbuilder after delivery.
Little was known about the reasons for the return, but German media cited a number of crucial "software and hardware failures" that rendered the warship useless in combat situations.
Software failure was of particular importance as the ships of the Baden-Wuerttemberg class will be piloted by a crew of 120 sailors – that’s only half of the crew of the older Bremen frigates.
It also turned out that the ship was too heavy, reducing its performance and limiting the Navy's ability for future updates.
The 7,000-ton Rhineland-Palatinate is said to be twice as heavy as similar ships used by the Germans during World War II.
In addition to hardware failures, the price of the project, which includes training the crew, is also becoming a problem.
It is said to have reached a staggering $3.1 billion ($3.6 billion), with an initial price of $2.2 billion.
The problems with the latest frigates are becoming even more important in light of recent warnings that Germany's naval power is shrinking.
Hans-Peter Bartels, head of the German government's defence committee, admitted earlier this year that the fleet is "running out of deployment-ready ships."
The official said the problem has grown over time because the old ships were taken out of service without being replaced.
He complained that none of the Baden-Wuerttemberg-class frigates were ready to join the fleet.
National Trust sneaks into the secret life of bats
New research from an area in the Scottish Highlands is trying to reveal how bats use the landscape when hunting.
The hope is that the findings will shed light on the behavior of the unique flying mammals and will help in the work of future conservation efforts.
The study is conducted by scientists from the National Trust of Scotland and follows common bats, dwarf bats, long-eared bats and water bats at Inverewe Gardens in Wester Ross.
Special recording equipment is placed in carefully selected locations in the area to record the activities of the bats throughout the season.
Data is also collected by staff from NTS and volunteers using handheld detectors.
In-depth analyses of the sound recordings will reveal the frequencies of the bat calls and show which species does what.
To produce a detailed landscape picture of their behaviour, a report and a map of the habitat are made.
Conservation advisor for NTS Rob Dewar hopes the results reveal which areas of the habitat are most important and how they are used by the different species.
This knowledge can help determine the benefits of habitat conservation efforts such as the establishment of meadows and how best to preserve woodlands for bats and similar species.
The number of bats in Scotland and the UK has fallen dramatically over the past 100 years.
They are threatened by buildings and urban expansion projects that affect the nests and restrict their habitat.
Wind turbines and lighting can also pose a danger, as can fly traps, chemical treatment of building materials and attacks from pets.
In fact, bats are not blind.
But because they primarily hunt at night, their ears are more useful than their eyes.
They use an advanced echolocation technique to find insects and fly around obstacles.
NTS, which is responsible for the preservation of more than 270 historic buildings, 38 important gardens and 76,000 hectares of land around the country, takes bats very seriously.
They have ten trained experts who often collect data, inspect nests and sometimes conduct rescue operations.
The organisation has even made Scotland's first and only dedicated bat reserve at the area around Threave in Dumfries and Galloway, home to eight out of ten of Scotland's bat species.
The area's caretaker, David Thompson, says it is an ideal territory for them.
"Here at Threave we have a really good area for bats," he said.
"We have old buildings, a lot of old trees and the whole good habitat.
There’s a lot you don’t know about bats, so working here and elsewhere can help you understand what they need to thrive.”
He stresses the importance of looking for bats before performing maintenance tasks on properties, as the destruction of a single nest can kill up to 400 females and cubs, thereby risking the extinction of an entire local population.
Bats are protected and it is illegal to kill, annoy or disturb them or their nests.
Elisabeth Ferrell, the Scottish project manager for the Bat Conservation Trust, has called on the public to lend a hand.
She said, "We still have a lot to learn about our bats, and for many of the species we have, we don't know how populations evolve."
Ronaldo rejects rape charges while lawyers sue German magazine
Cristiano Ronaldo has called rape charges against him "fake news" and says that people "will promote themselves" by using his name.
His lawyers are preparing to sue the German news media Der Spiegel, which brought the accusations.
The attacker from Portugal and Juventus has been accused of raping an American woman, Kathryn Mayorga, in a hotel room in Las Vegas in 2009.
It is alleged that he paid her $375,000 to keep it secret, Der Spiegel wrote on Friday.
A few hours after the allegations were made public, 33-year-old Ronaldo spoke to his 142 million followers on Instagram Live, criticizing the information for being "fake news".
"No, no, no, no.
What they said today is fake news," the five-time winner of the Ballon d'Or told the camera.
"They want to promote themselves by using my name.
It's normal.
They'll be famous by saying my name, but that's part of the job.
I'm a happy man and all is well," added the player smiling.
Ronaldo's lawyers are preparing to sue Der Spiegel over the charges, which they have called "an unforgivable disclosure of suspicions about the privacy sphere".
Lawyer Christian Schertz says the player would seek compensation for "moral corruption in a class similar to the accusation, which is probably one of the most serious violations of personal rights in recent years."
The incident allegedly occurred in June 2009 in a room at the Palms Hotel and Casino in Las Vegas.
After meeting each other at a nightclub, Ronaldo and Mayorga allegedly went back to the player's room, where he allegedly raped her anally, according to the filed report in the district court in Clark County, Nevada.
Mayorga alleges that Ronald fell to his knees after the alleged incident, saying he was "a good guy 99% of the time" gripped by "the one percent".
The lawsuits allege that Ronaldo confirmed that the couple had sex, but that there was consent to it.
Mayorga also claims that she went to the police and had her injuries photographed in a hospital, but that she later agreed to an out-of-court settlement because she felt "fear of retaliation" and worried about being "publicly shamed".
The 34-year-old now says she will overturn the deal, as she is still deeply affected by the alleged incident.
Ronaldo was faced with a move from Manchester United to Real Madrid when the incident was supposed to have occurred, and changed to Italian big club Juventus for 100 million euros this summer.
Brexit: Britain 'will forever regret' losing automakers
Britain "will regret it forever" if it lost its status as a leading car manufacturer worldwide after Brexit, business minister Greg Clark said.
He added that it was "concerning" that Toyota UK had told the BBC that if Britain left the EU without a deal, it would temporarily lower production at the factory in Burnaston near Derby.
"We need a deal," Clark said.
The Japanese automaker said that longer waiting time at the border in the event of a no-deal Brexit could cost jobs.
The Burnaston plant, which produces Toyota’s Auris and Avensis, produced nearly 150,000 cars last year, 90% of which were exported to the rest of the EU.
"The way I see it, production will stop at our factory if the UK leaves the EU at the end of March," Burnaston CEO Marvin Cooke said.
Other British car manufacturers, including Honda, BMW and Jaguar Land Rover, express fears of leaving the EU without a cross-border trade deal.
For example, BMW says it will close its Mini factory in Oxford one month after Brexit.
The main concern of car manufacturers has to do with risks to the supply chain in the event of a no-deal exit.
Toyota’s production runs on a tight schedule, with parts arriving every 37 minutes from suppliers in both the UK and the EU.
If the UK leaves the EU without an agreement on 29 March, problems could arise at the border, which, according to the automotive industry, could lead to delays and a lack of parts.
It would be impossible for Toyota to store more than a day's production at the Derbyshire plant, and then production would be stopped, the company said.
Clark says Theresa May's Chequers plan for future negotiations with the EU is "composed to precisely avoid these checks at the border."
"We need to have a deal. We want the best deal, which not only allows us – as I call it – to enjoy our current success, but to seize this opportunity," he told BBC Radio 4's Today programme.
"The opinions of Toyota and other manufacturers indicate that we need to be able to continue what have been successful supply chains."
Toyota could not say how long production would have stopped, but in the long run higher prices would reduce the factory's competitiveness, which will ultimately cost jobs.
Peter Tsouvallaris, who has worked at Burnaston for 24 years and is a joint shop steward at the factory, says his members are becoming increasingly concerned: "My experience tells me that as soon as these jobs disappear, they won't come back."
A spokesman for the government said, "We have proposed a precise and credible plan for our future relationship with the EU."
Trump’s meeting with Rosenstein may be delayed again, White House says
Donald Trump's important meeting with Deputy Attorney General Rod Rosenstein could "be postponed one more week" as the showdown around Supreme Court nominee Brett Kavanaugh continues, the White House said on Sunday.
Rosenstein looks over the shoulder of special prosecutor Robert Mueller during his investigation into Russian election interference, connections between Trump’s aides and Russia, and the president’s possible obstruction of justice.
Whether Trump will fire the deputy attorney general and thereby risk Mueller’s independence has been a topic of gossip in Washington for months.
The New York Times wrote earlier this month that Rosenstein was considering wearing a microphone to record conversations with Trump and the possibility of dismissing the president via the 25th paragraph.
Rosenstein denied the news.
But last Monday, he went to the White House, and the rumor was that he was going to quit.
Instead, a meeting was scheduled for Thursday with Trump, who was then at the UN headquarters in New York.
Trump said he would "prefer not" to fire Rosenstein, but the meeting was delayed to avoid a coincidence with the Senate Judiciary Committee hearing where Kavanaugh and Christine Blasey Ford, who have accused him of sexual assault, were to testify.
On Friday, Trump ordered a week-long FBI investigation into the allegations against Kavanaugh, delaying the Senate election.
Trump press secretary Sarah Sanders was on Fox News on Sunday.
When asked about the meeting with Rosenstein, she said: "There is no set date. It could be this week. I can also imagine that it could be pushed a week with all that is going on in the Supreme Court.
But we'll see, and I like to always keep the press updated."
Some journalists would challenge that claim: Sanders has not held a press conference at the White House since September 10.
The host Chris Wallace asked her why.
Sanders said that the lack of press conferences was not due to television journalists' games for the gallery, but added, "I don't disagree that they are playing up to the camera."
She then said that the direct contact between Trump and the press will be increased.
"The president takes more questions from the press than any president before him," she said, adding without quoting a source: "We've looked at the numbers."
Press conferences will still take place, Sanders said, but "if the press has the opportunity to ask the president of the United States direct questions, it's infinitely better than talking to me.
We're trying to provide ample opportunity for it, and you've seen us do it over the last few weeks, and it's going to be in the place of the press conference when you can talk to the President of the United States."
Trump often takes questions when he leaves the White House or attends open hearings or press conferences with senior guests.
Press conferences with Trump alone are rare.
This week in New York, the president showed why, when he did an impromptu and sometimes mysterious figure in front of the journalists present.
Health Minister contacts EU staff in Scottish health care after Brexit concerns
The Minister of Health has written to the EU staff working in Scotland's NHS, to express the country's gratitude and desire that they stay after Brexit.
Jeane Freeman, a member of the Scottish Parliament, sent a letter less than half a year before Britain withdraws from the EU.
The Government of Scotland has already committed itself to paying for the applications for permanent residence of EU citizens working in its delegated public sector.
In his letter, Freeman wrote: "During the summer, negotiations between the UK and the EU on withdrawal have continued and it appears that decisions are expected in the autumn.
But the UK government has also stepped up their preparations for a possible Brexit without a deal.
I know it must be a very uncertain period for all of you.
That is why I would like to reiterate how much I appreciate the efforts each individual employee has made, regardless of their nationality.
Colleagues from within and outside the EU bring valuable experience and skills that strengthen and improve the work of the healthcare system to the benefit of patients and local communities.
Scotland is definitely your home, and we would very much like you to stay.
Christion Abercrombie undergoes emergency surgery after head injury
The linebacker from the Tennessee State Tigers, Christion Abercrombie was acutely operated after suffering a head injury in Saturday's 31-27 defeat to the Vanderbilt Commodores, reports Tennessee's Mike Organ.
First coach for Tennessee State, Rod Reed, told reporters that the incident occurred before the break.
"He went out to the sidelines and just fell around out there," Reed said.
Trainers and medical staff gave Abercrombie oxygen on the sidelines before putting him on a stretcher and taking him in for further examination.
A Tennessee State spokesman told Chris Harris of WSMV in Nashville, Tennessee that Abercrombie's surgery at Vanderbilt Medical Center was over.
Harris added that there are "no details on the type or extent of the injury yet", and Tennessee State is trying to figure out when he sustained the injury.
Abercrombie is studying in his sophomore year and is embarking on his first season in Tennessee State after a shift from Illinois.
He had five tackles on Saturday before leaving the game, giving him 18 tackles overall this season.
Foreign buyers are charged higher stamp duty when buying a house in the UK
Foreign buyers are charged higher stamp duty when buying a property in the UK. The extra money, according to the Conservative Party, is supposed to help the homeless.
This move should dampen Corbyn's success in attracting young voters.
The higher stamp duty will hit those who do not pay taxes in the UK.
The Ministry of Finance expects that it will raise 120 million euros a year for the homeless.
Theresa May will today propose that foreign buyers be charged a higher stamp duty when buying properties in the UK, for the benefit of the homeless.
The move will be seen as an attempt to counter Jeremy Corbyn's success in attracting young voters with promises of cheaper housing and going after those with the highest income.
The increase in stamp duty will affect people and businesses that do not pay taxes in the UK. The proceeds from this will be used for the government’s fight to ensure that everyone has a place to sleep.
The additional fee, which is added to the current stamp duty and the higher levels introduced two years ago on multi-home purchases and purchases to rent out, can reach 3%.
The Ministry of Finance expects that it can raise 120 million euros per year.
It is estimated that 13% of new construction in London is purchased by people living abroad, which causes prices to rise and makes it harder for first-time buyers to gain a foothold in the housing market.
Many rich areas of the country, especially in the capital, have become "ghost cities" due to the high number of foreign buyers who spend most of their time outside the country.
The new bill comes just weeks after Boris Johnson proposed a cut in stamp duty to make it easier for young people to buy their first home.
He accused major construction companies of keeping property prices up by buying land they don't use. He asked May to drop quotas on cheap housing to solve Britain's "shameful housing situation."
Corbyn has proposed an eye-catching series of housing reforms, including controlling rent prices and depriving the landlord of the ability to put people on the street if they comply with the lease.
He will also strengthen the ability to build public housing.
May said: "Last year I said that I would use my presidency to restore the British dream; that life is getting better with each generation.
And that means repairing our non-functioning housing market.
Britain will always be open to people who want to live, work and build a life here.
But it cannot be that it is as easy for foreign companies and people living outside the UK to buy homes as it is for hard-working Britons.
For far too many, the dream of owning a home has become too distant, and the unworthiness of sleeping on the street is still far too widespread."
Jack Ross: 'My ultimate goal is to become Scotland's coach'
The head of Sunderland, Jack Ross, says that his "ultimate goal" is at some point to become Scotland's coach.
The Scotsman of 42 is enjoying the challenge of reviving the club from the North East, which now has third place in League One, three points from the top.
He switched to the Stadium of Light this summer after leading St Mirren back in the Scottish Premiership last season.
"I wanted to play for my country as a player.
"I played one match with the B team and that was it", Ross told BBC Scotland's Sportsound.
"But I grew up seeing Scotland at Hampden with my father when I was a child, and it has always drawn in me.
However, that opportunity would only arise if I was successful in training clubs."
Ross' predecessors as coach of Sunderland are Dick Advocaat, David Moyes, Sam Allardyce, Martin O'Neill, Roy Keane, Gus Poyet and Paulo Di Canio.
The former coach of Alloa Athletic says he had no qualms about following such established names in such a large club and had previously rejected offers from Barnsley and Ipswich Town.
"Now I'm measuring success by whether or not I can get this club back in the Premier League.
From the structure and facilities of this club, it undoubtedly belongs in the Premier League," he said.
"It's not an easy task, but I'll probably only see myself as successful here if I can get the club back there."
Ross is only three years into his career as a coach after a period as an assistant coach at Dumbarton and a 15-month failure as part of the Hearts coaching staff.
He then helped Alloa to come back after being relegated to third-best ranks and transformed St Mirren from the relegation threat to title winners the following season.
And Ross says he feels more comfortable now than he ever did during his career playing for Clyde, Hartlepool, Falkirk, St Mirren and Hamilton Academical.
"It was probably a real crossroads," he remembers about the time in Alloa.
"I honestly thought the coaching was right for me, more right than being a player.
It sounds strange because I did well, served sensibly and had some success experiences.
But it can be hard to play.
There are many things that you have to go through on a weekly basis.
There is still that kind of stress and pressure as a coach, but it just feels right.
I've always wanted to train, and now I do. I haven't felt more comfortable with myself in my entire adult life."
You can hear the full interview on Sportsound on Sunday 30 September on Radio Scotland between 12.00 and 13.00 BST.
The best time for a beer is Saturdays at 5:30 p.m., study shows
The heat wave this summer has increased earnings for England's pubs, but has put restaurant chains under greater pressure.
Sales in pubs and bars increased by 2.7% in July, while sales in restaurants have declined 4.8%, figures show.
Peter Martin, a business consultant at CGA who collected the figures, said: "Continued sunshine and England's unexpectedly long World Cup have meant that July follows June's pattern of pubs experiencing upsells of 2.8%, except that the restaurants are harder hit now.
The decline of 1.8% in restaurants in June only got worse in July.
Pubs and bars with a focus on the sale of drinks fared best and saw progress corresponding to the decline of the restaurants.
Pubs with a focus on food suffered in the sun, but not as much as the restaurants.
It seems that people just want something to drink.
Across pub and bar chains, sales of beverages increased by 6.6% for the month, while food declined by 3.3%."
Paul Newman, who analyzes the service industry, said: “The results continue the trend we’ve seen since the end of April.
